{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11932"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.53,0.04,0.17,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4528"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1702"},{"type":"tags","id":"1703"},{"type":"tags","id":"2113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4866"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to his General Practitioner as his parents are worried that he has not undergone the full extent of puberty. He states he does not have much pubic hair and thinks his penile size has not grown. He has also noticed that his sense of smell has become impaired. He has a medical history of undescended testicles in his early childhood which self-corrected. He takes no regular medications and his vaccinations are up to date. On physical examination, scant pubic hair and normally descended testes are shown. Blood investigations show plasma testosterone, luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormones are all low.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normosmic hypogonadotropic hypogonadism","Kallman\u0027s syndrome","Sequelae from previous cryptorchidism","Klinefelter syndrome","5-alpha reductase deficiency"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKallman\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare genetic condition which results from deficient gonadotropin-releasing hormone leading to secondary hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, defined by a delay/absence of signs of puberty along with an absent/impaired sense of smell. Low FSH and LH levels suggest a secondary cause of hypogonadism in contrast to primary hypogonadism which would show elevated levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKallman\u0027s syndrome is one of two subtypes of congenital hypogonadotropic hypogonadism with the latter being \u003Cstrong\u003Enormosmic hypogonadotropic hypogonadism\u003C/strong\u003E. The only difference between Kallman\u0027s syndrome and normosmic hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is the absence/presence of smell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is unlikely to be \u003Cstrong\u003Esequelae from previous cryptorchidism \u003C/strong\u003Eas it was self-corrected early on.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlinefelter syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis a rare chromosomal disorder characterised by karyotype 47, XXY. This causes impaired development of the testicles with resultant testosterone underproduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5-alpha reductase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E leads to a deficiency of dihydrotestosterone, so that genetically male patients are only affected. 5-alpha reductase deficiency phenotype can vary from underdeveloped male genitalia to fully developed female genitalia. It is not associated with hyposmia/anosmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs a note of interest, there are many challenges in differentiating Constitutional Delay of Puberty, a much more common condition, from Kallman\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Kallman syndrome is a rare cause of secondary hypogonadism characterised by absent or delayed puberty (more often in males) and is associated with a loss of smell."],"references":["Nepal P, Kumar D, Ojili V. Abnormal descent of the testis and its complications: A multimodality imaging review. SA J Radiol. 2018;22(1):1374. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31754510/","Laitinen EM, Vaaralahti K, Tommiska J, et al. Incidence, phenotypic features and molecular genetics of Kallmann syndrome in Finland. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2011;6:41. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21682876/","Kumar G, Barboza-Meca JJ. 5 Alpha Reductase Deficiency. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539904/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29397"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29397"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-21T14:08:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-21T14:08:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44510"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi